Solution: I need to find the number of red balls in the second urn.

**Setting up the problem:**

Urn 1: 8 red, 7 blue (total 15 balls)
Urn 2: x red, 9 blue (total x + 9 balls)

**Probability of drawing two balls of the same color:**

Two balls are the same color if:
- Both are red, OR
- Both are blue

P(both red) = P(red from urn 1) × P(red from urn 2)
$$P(\text{both red}) = \frac{8}{15} \times \frac{x}{x+9}$$

P(both blue) = P(blue from urn 1) × P(blue from urn 2)
$$P(\text{both blue}) = \frac{7}{15} \times \frac{9}{x+9}$$

**Total probability:**
$$P(\text{same color}) = \frac{8}{15} \times \frac{x}{x+9} + \frac{7}{15} \times \frac{9}{x+9}$$

$$\frac{151}{300} = \frac{8x}{15(x+9)} + \frac{63}{15(x+9)}$$

$$\frac{151}{300} = \frac{8x + 63}{15(x+9)}$$

**Cross multiply:**
$$151 \times 15(x+9) = 300(8x + 63)$$

$$2265(x+9) = 300(8x + 63)$$

$$2265x + 20385 = 2400x + 18900$$

$$20385 - 18900 = 2400x - 2265x$$

$$1485 = 135x$$

$$x = \frac{1485}{135} = 11$$

**Verification:**
$$P(\text{same color}) = \frac{8 \times 11}{15 \times 20} + \frac{7 \times 9}{15 \times 20}$$

$$= \frac{88}{300} + \frac{63}{300} = \frac{151}{300}$$ ✓

